2500|$|Every <b>surreal</b> <b>number</b> is a game, {{but not all}} {{games are}} surreal numbers, e.g. the game [...] 0 } is not a <b>surreal</b> <b>number.</b> [...] The class of games is more general than the surreals, and has a simpler definition, but lacks some of the nicer {{properties}} of surreal numbers. [...] The class of surreal numbers forms a field, but the class of games does not. [...] The surreals have a total order: given any two surreals, they are either equal, or one {{is greater than the}} other. [...] The games have only a partial order: there exist pairs of games that are neither equal, greater than, nor less than each other. [...] Each <b>surreal</b> <b>number</b> is either positive, negative, or zero. [...] Each game is either positive, negative, zero, or fuzzy (incomparable with zero, such as {1|−1}).|$|E
