25|$|This {{isomorphism}} {{makes the}} <b>surreal</b> <b>numbers</b> into a valued field where the valuation is the additive inverse of the exponent {{of the leading}} term in the Conway normal form, e.g., ν(ω) = -1. The valuation ring then consists of the finite <b>surreal</b> <b>numbers</b> (numbers with a real and/or an infinitesimal part). The reason for the sign inversion is that the exponents in the Conway normal form constitute a reverse well-ordered set, whereas Hahn series are formulated in terms of (non-reversed) well-ordered subsets of the value group.|$|R
